          <div class='slide' id="guideline0">
            <div class="container">
              <div class="guide-style">
                <h2 style="text-decoration: underline" class="darkfont"> Guidelines for Meditation</h2>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Choose a practice that is good for you</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">Pick something that seems pleasant for you to do, as opposed to a chore. Something you might even look forward to.</h4>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Set aside the time</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">Make a small commitment at first, but one you can do every day or the same day each week. Ideally, your commitment would also be for the same time.</h4>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Don’t do too much!</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">Making too large a time commitment can get in the way of establishing a routine. Don’t underestimate the power of practicing 5 minutes every day, or going to a strong class once per week.</h4>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Keep your life as it is</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">There is no need to quit your job, leave your partner, and move to a cave in the mountains. The day-to-day travails of life can often propel our practice forward. But at first, just add a simple, sweet practice and let everything else be. </h4>
                
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class='slide' id="guideline1">
            <div class="container">
              <div class="guide-style">
                <h1 style="text-decoration: underline" class="darkfont">During Practice</h1>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Return to your focus</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">Really, this is how you meditate. Whatever you choose to practice, you will find your mind wanders. It's ok, that’s what the mind does! The only thing to do is notice, and bring the mind back to your practice. Like lovingly redirecting a child back to their favorite toy.</h4>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Be consistent</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">Not every day is going to be the Greatest Meditation Ever. We must trust our practice is working even if we can't always tell that it is.</h4>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Love your practice</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">Your practice should give you an internal smile most of the time</h4>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Your practice is yours</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">It is tempting to compare ourselves to others or feel like we “should” be doing this or that. Try to trust that you have picked the best practice for yourself, and let that practice take care of itself. No need to worry!</h4>
                <br>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- This will be the slide section for the TIPS section -->

          <div class='slide' id="guideline2">
            <div class="container">
              <div class="guide-style">
                <h1 style="text-decoration: underline" class="darkfont">Tips - Halp! My Mind Is Argh!</h1>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Make a list</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">If thoughts overwhelm your practice and you feel the argh, stop and make a list of all the things that come up. When they’re all down, go back to your practice.</h4>
                <h3 class="darkfont">The houseguest</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">Imagine your mind is a party. You are the host, thoughts are the guests. Welcome the guests, and let them know that you will get chat with them when you are done preparing their party, i.e., your practice. (This is a recommendation from Swami Ashokananda from Integral Yoga Institute).</h4>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Fill your mind with good things</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">It can be helpful to moderate what you read and watch to support your practice. If you shift your reading and watching habits to include things that are related to your practice, it is easier to get into your practice mode when the time comes.</h4>
                <br>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="slide" id="guideline3">
            <div class="container">
              <div class="guide-style">
                <h1 style="text-decoration: underline" class="darkfont">Tips - Seek Company for Your Journey</h1>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Find like-minded People</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">Being with people who are of a like mind, who have a practice, is a nice way to support your work. Knowing there are people experiencing similar troubles and triumphs can be very calming.</h4>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Find a teacher</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">There is no substitute for having access to someone who has completed the journey you are beginning. They can help in ways that are hard to imagine. Finding a proper guide can be a long process, but for %99.99 of us our practice can only go so far without one. There is no rush- do your chosen practice, and start looking into who teaches similar things. That will take care of it.</h4>
                <h3 class="darkfont">Talk therapy</h3>
                <h4 class="darkfont">While dredging up old baggage is never really useful, having insight into your emotional life can bring insights into your habits and bring clarity to your intention. And help you let go of things you find you no longer need.</h4>
                <br>
              </div>
